---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="About Jeffrey"
  description="Three decades in law enforcement, security and protective services. The operator who built JF Self Defense and why he refuses to teach martial arts."
  activeNav="about"
  bodyLabel="02 About Jeffrey">

<!-- PAGE HERO -->
<section class="trainers-hero about-hero">
  <div class="trainers-hero-bg">
    <img src="/assets/hero-home-v2.jpg" alt="" />
  </div>
  <div class="wrap trainers-hero-overlay">
    <div class="crumb">
      <span>JF SELF DEFENSE</span><span class="sep">/</span><span class="here">ABOUT</span>
    </div>
    <h1 class="display h1 about-hero-h1">
      <span class="about-hero-pre">There is no winning in a fight<br/>We train you to</span>
      <span class="about-hero-main"><span class="red">NEVER HAVE ONE</span></span>
    </h1>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- PHILOSOPHY SECTION — the distinction -->
<section class="section section-tight">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="section-head">
      <div>
        <span class="section-head-num">THE DISTINCTION</span>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h2 class="display h2 section-head-title">
          Martial arts teach you to fight.<br/>
          We teach you to <span style="color:var(--red);">survive</span>.
        </h2>
        <p class="lede" style="margin-top:24px;">
          Most schools sell technique. The art of throwing a punch, blocking a kick,
          countering a knife. Beautiful, demanding work — and a different discipline
          from what we teach.
        </p>
        <p class="body" style="margin-top:18px;max-width:60ch;">
          Self defense is not a martial art. It is a survival system that borrows
          from the martial arts only where the borrowing serves the survival.
          A martial artist trains to win the fight. We train you to never be in one.
          And if you are — to leave it as fast as possible, by whatever route works.
        </p>
        <p class="body" style="margin-top:18px;max-width:60ch;">
          When a martial artist demonstrates a knife defence, they teach you to engage
          the blade. When we demonstrate one, the first answer is the same as the
          last: <strong style="color:var(--ink);">run</strong>. The technique exists
          only for the seconds when running is gone.
        </p>

        <div class="pullquote" style="margin-top:48px;max-width:64ch;">
          <p class="q">"There is no winning in a fight. Even when you <span class="red">win</span>, you lose — your time, your money, your peace, sometimes your freedom. The only fight worth being in is the one you walked away from."</p>
        </div>

        <p class="body" style="margin-top:18px;max-width:60ch;">
          This is why our students leave class talking about awareness, distance,
          posture and exits — long before they ever talk about strikes. By the time
          a strike matters, four better options have already failed. Our job is to
          make sure those four options never fail.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- BIO -->
<section class="wrap">
  <div class="about-bio">
    <aside class="about-portrait">
      <div class="img">
        <img src="/assets/studio.jpg" alt="Jeffrey Fleury teaching at JF Self Defense" />
      </div>
      <div class="cap">
        <span>JEFFREY FLEURY</span>
        <span>PAYA LEBAR &middot; 2024</span>
      </div>
    </aside>
    <article class="about-text">
      <span class="eyebrow"><span class="dot"></span>WHO STARTED THIS, AND WHY</span>
      <p class="lede" style="margin-top:20px;">
        The philosophy above is not academic. It was built by Jeffrey Fleury over three
        decades in law enforcement, private security and protective services — long
        before he ever taught a paying student.
      </p>
      <p>
        Jeffrey holds a Bachelor of Science and is a certified International Certified
        Protection Specialist (ICPS) — a credential earned, not bought, by working
        professionals in the protective services industry. He founded JF Self Defense in
        Singapore in 2009 with a single conviction: the country needed a self-defense
        school that wasn't really about fighting.
      </p>

      <div class="pullquote">
        <p class="q">"I don't teach martial arts. I teach you how to <span class="red">avoid</span> needing them — and what to do in the seconds when avoidance fails."</p>
      </div>

      <p>
        His critique of the traditional martial arts world is sharp but never
        dismissive: forms, kata and belts were built for a different era and a
        different threat. They are beautiful, demanding, and not always honest about
        the gap between the dojo floor and the street, the carpark, the train at
        midnight. Jeffrey closes that gap with three decades of accumulated
        operational judgment — what he calls <em>working memory</em>: the catalogue
        of situations he has personally responded to, broken down, and rebuilt as
        teachable decisions.
      </p>
      <p>
        He teaches with a working operator's pragmatism and, as his students
        repeatedly note, an unmistakable warmth. Humour is not decoration in his
        classroom — it is a teaching tool. A laugh resets the nervous system, and a
        nervous system that can reset is one that can think under pressure. Everyone
        who has trained with Jeffrey for more than a few sessions can quote him.
      </p>

      <div class="timeline">
        <div class="timeline-row">
          <div class="timeline-year">1991 — 2008</div>
          <div class="timeline-title">Law enforcement &amp; protective services</div>
          <div class="timeline-body">
            Eighteen years across uniformed and plainclothes work in Singapore —
            patrol, investigations, and close-protection assignments for corporate
            and visiting principals.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-row">
          <div class="timeline-year">2004</div>
          <div class="timeline-title">BSc · applied to operator judgment</div>
          <div class="timeline-body">
            Completed Bachelor of Science studies alongside active service. The
            academic discipline shaped how Jeffrey teaches: every drill has a
            documented rationale, every progression a measurable test.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-row">
          <div class="timeline-year">2007</div>
          <div class="timeline-title">ICPS — Certified Protection Specialist</div>
          <div class="timeline-body">
            International credential earned through examined operational experience —
            the bar professional close protection officers are measured against
            globally.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-row">
          <div class="timeline-year">2009</div>
          <div class="timeline-title">Founded JF Self Defense, Singapore</div>
          <div class="timeline-body">
            Opened the first iteration of the school to civilian students — women,
            families, expat professionals — with one promise: practical, scalable,
            honest training.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-row">
          <div class="timeline-year">2014 — present</div>
          <div class="timeline-title">Corporate &amp; institutional training</div>
          <div class="timeline-body">
            Trusted by SUSS, Celanese, Sloane Clinic, National Healthcare Group,
            Emerson, Latham &amp; Watkins and Teck Whye Secondary School — among
            others. Joined by son Ryan Fleury as co-instructor in recent years.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3 class="display h3" style="margin-top:64px;margin-bottom:16px;">Why his teaching looks different.</h3>
      <p>
        Jeffrey programmes for the bodies in front of him. A working mother in her
        forties does not need the same drills as a security officer in his twenties,
        and pretending otherwise is the single most common failure of self-defense
        instruction worldwide. JF classes scale: the underlying decisions are the
        same; the implementation is rebuilt for the student.
      </p>
      <p>
        He refuses the macho theatre that surrounds most combat schools. There are no
        weapons walls, no cage imagery, no "warrior" branding. His students are
        teachers, doctors, lawyers, engineers, mothers, teenagers and the
        occasional working officer. The classroom looks like Singapore looks.
      </p>

      <div class="pullquote" style="margin-bottom:0;">
        <p class="q">"A fight you avoid is a fight you <span class="red">won</span>. The rest of what we teach exists for the day you can't."</p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</section>

